---
import { Code } from "astro:components";
import GuideLayout from "../../components/GuideLayout.astro";

const send = `import gleam/json
import watershed_js

// Broadcast which station this surveyor is inspecting. Fire-and-forget:
// nothing is stored, nothing is sequenced, no one converges on it.
pub fn announce_focus(doc, station: String) {
  watershed_js.submit_ripple(
    doc,
    ripple_type: "focus",
    content: json.object([#("station", json.string(station))]),
  )
}`;

const recv = `import gleam/dynamic/decode
import gleam/option.{Some}
import watershed_js

// React to every peer's ripples. \`ripple_client_id\` tells you who sent it;
// the content is left as Dynamic for you to decode per type.
watershed_js.subscribe_ripples(doc, fn(ripple) {
  case watershed_js.ripple_type(ripple) {
    Some("focus") -> {
      let decoded =
        decode.run(
          watershed_js.ripple_content(ripple),
          decode.at(["station"], decode.string),
        )
      case decoded, watershed_js.ripple_client_id(ripple) {
        Ok(station), Some(peer) -> move_peer_marker(peer, station)
        _, _ -> Nil
      }
    }
    Some("recheck") -> flash_recheck_request(ripple)
    _ -> Nil
  }
})`;
---

<GuideLayout
  slug="ripples"
  description="Step four of the watershed build guide: ripples are document-scoped, non-sequenced broadcasts to every other connected client — the escape hatch for live cursors, presence, and reactions that must not become part of the document's converged state."
>
  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Not everything belongs in the document</h2>
    <p>
      Some signals are about <em>now</em>, not about state: which station a
      surveyor is looking at, a cursor position, a “re-check this” nudge, a
      thumbs-up. Storing those in a channel would be wrong — they’d be sequenced,
      summarised, and replayed to everyone who joins an hour later, long after
      they stopped meaning anything.
    </p>
    <p>
      A <strong>ripple</strong> is watershed’s answer: a document-scoped,
      non-sequenced broadcast delivered to every <em>other</em> connected client
      and then gone. No ordering, no storage, no convergence — deliberately. It’s
      the ephemeral tier that sits alongside your channels.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Send a ripple</h2>
    <p>
      A ripple is a <code>type</code> tag plus a JSON payload.
      <code>submit_ripple</code> broadcasts it and returns nothing — there’s no
      ack to await, because there’s no state to change. Bench Book announces the
      station a surveyor is inspecting:
    </p>
    <figure class="g-code">
      <Code code={send} lang="gleam" theme="css-variables" />
    </figure>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Receive ripples</h2>
    <p>
      <code>subscribe_ripples</code> hands every inbound ripple to your handler.
      Match on <code>ripple_type</code>, decode <code>ripple_content</code> at
      the boundary, and use <code>ripple_client_id</code> to know which peer it
      came from — enough to render a live roster of who is looking where.
    </p>
    <figure class="g-code">
      <Code code={recv} lang="gleam" theme="css-variables" />
    </figure>
    <div class="g-note">
      <p>
        <strong>Ripples for now, channels for state.</strong> A ripple never
        lands in a summary, so a client that joins later won’t see it — which is
        exactly right for a cursor and exactly wrong for a reading. If a
        late-joiner must see it, it belongs in a channel, not a ripple.
      </p>
      <p>
        On the BEAM, <code>subscribe_ripples(doc)</code> returns a
        <code>Subject(Ripple)</code> you receive on instead of taking a callback —
        the same signal, shaped for OTP.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="g-block">
    <h2>Presence is ripples with a heartbeat</h2>
    <p>
      Raw ripples are stateless, so a peer who goes quiet leaves their last
      marker stuck on screen. <strong>Presence</strong> layers the missing
      lifecycle on top: each client heartbeats its payload on a ripple, and a
      peer whose heartbeat lapses past a TTL is dropped from the roster. You
      rarely hand-roll that — the next step wires the built-in presence driver
      to your UI as a single effect.
    </p>
    <p>
      For how this tier behaves at runtime — the heartbeat cadence, the TTL, and
      why a ripple never survives a reconnect — see the runtime note on
      <a href="/runtime/presence">presence &amp; ripples</a>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="g-out">
    <span class="annot">You can now</span>
    <p>
      Broadcast live, throwaway signals — cursors, focus, reactions — to every
      other client without polluting the document’s converged state, and decode
      them safely on the way in.
    </p>
  </div>
</GuideLayout>
